This is a video that was created by Dan Simons

00:07:10.321 --> 00:07:15.039
this year. He calls it "the monkey business
illusion" and the idea is that expecting the

00:07:15.039 --> 00:07:19.639
unexpected, or knowing that your attention
is limited and you might not notice things,

00:07:19.639 --> 00:07:24.280
doesn't necessarily enable you to notice all
the unexpected things that are going on around

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:28.190
you. If you had known in advance that something
might change color, you might have picked

00:07:28.190 --> 00:07:32.410
up on the curtain, but then you might not
have noticed the gorilla. So, there's no,

00:07:32.410 --> 00:07:41.810
the trick to this is deeper than just something
you don't notice. [pause] In psychology jargon,

00:07:41.810 --> 00:07:45.430
this phenomenon is known as "inattentional
blindness" now and this is a term that was

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:49.520
popularized by Arien Mack and Irvin Rock in
their book of the same name. And the idea

00:07:49.520 --> 00:07:52.800
is that when we're not paying attention to
something, it can be as though we're actually

00:07:52.800 --> 00:07:57.590
blind to it. It's as though the thing isn't
there or as though we don't see it at all.

00:07:57.590 --> 00:08:00.910
It's not as though we should have catch a
faint glimpse of it, but not a really good

00:08:00.910 --> 00:08:04.930
perception of it. When people are told afterwards
that there was a gorilla walking across in

00:08:04.930 --> 00:08:08.880
our original video that they didn't see, they
don't suddenly say, "Oh, yeah. There was a

00:08:08.880 --> 00:08:12.471
gorilla, but I just forgot to mention it to
you." Instead, they say, "No way. There was

00:08:12.471 --> 00:08:16.650
no gorilla there." Or, in the original experiment
where we had video tapes, they said, "Well,

00:08:16.650 --> 00:08:20.460
show me the tape again," and we would rewind
it and play it again and they'd say, "Well,

00:08:20.460 --> 00:08:23.030
that wasn't there in the first place. Maybe
you switched the tapes on me or used some

00:08:23.030 --> 00:08:26.470
kind of sleight of hand or something like
that." On the other hand, people who see the

00:08:26.470 --> 00:08:30.320
gorilla, or probably the people who saw the
color change or the person walk away this

00:08:30.320 --> 00:08:33.839
time, think it's very clear and obvious and
they are surprised that other people missed

00:08:33.839 --> 00:08:39.249
it. So, as we thought about this experiment
more and more, we realized that it wasn't

00:08:39.249 --> 00:08:43.099
just telling us something about inattentional
blindness, it wasn't just a dramatic demonstration

00:08:43.099 --> 00:08:46.629
of inattentional blindness and incidentally,
just to illustrate how dramatic a demonstration

00:08:46.629 --> 00:08:51.809
this is, other researchers later ran this
experiment using an eye tracking device, which

00:08:51.809 --> 00:08:55.329
records exactly where subjects are looking
at all times and found that some subjects

00:08:55.329 --> 00:08:59.509
who missed the gorilla in the original video
had actually looked right at it for up to

00:08:59.509 --> 00:09:03.230
a full second and still missed it. So, it's
not just that their eyes happened to be pushed,

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:08.429
pointing the wrong way. There's actually some
kind of cognitive blindness to this thing.

00:09:08.429 --> 00:09:11.380
And that's really interesting, but the more
we thought about it, the more we thought there

00:09:11.380 --> 00:09:16.350
was something even more surprising about it.
And that was, in fact, the surprise that people

00:09:16.350 --> 00:09:20.360
have about the results of this experiment.
It really conflicts with some deep belief

00:09:20.360 --> 00:09:24.569
we have about how our minds work. Something
about our experience tells us that we really

00:09:24.569 --> 00:09:27.939
should be noticing all the important things
that happen, especially if they're right in

00:09:27.939 --> 00:09:32.040
front of our eyes and they last for a full
nine seconds, like our original gorilla thumping

00:09:32.040 --> 00:09:37.390
event did. And this belief that we're noticing
and paying attention to much more of the world

00:09:37.390 --> 00:09:44.050
around us then we really are, is what we've
called the illusion of attention. The illusion

00:09:44.050 --> 00:09:49.239
is that we're noticing and paying attention
to far more than we actually are. Now, we

00:09:49.239 --> 00:09:54.499
call this an illusion deliberately. It's in
some ways by analogy to visual illusions.

00:09:54.499 --> 00:09:58.920
So, this is a famous visual illusion. Look
at these two tables and raise your hand if

00:09:58.920 --> 00:10:04.860
you think the table on the left is longer
than the table on the right. OK, so I'm gonna

00:10:04.860 --> 00:10:08.089
raise my hand, too, because to me, the one
on the left definitely looks longer than the

00:10:08.089 --> 00:10:12.589
one on the right. Now, if I had a nice, clever
animation, I could rotate that table on the

00:10:12.589 --> 00:10:16.239
left and overlay it on the table on the right
and you would see that they are the exact

00:10:16.239 --> 00:10:20.899
same dimensions in all respects. And it is
a pure illusion that the one on the left looks

00:10:20.899 --> 00:10:27.250
long and narrow and the one on the right looks
wide. It has to do with perspective and the

00:10:27.250 --> 00:10:31.499
way our perceptual system actually wants to
experience a three-dimensional world as opposed

00:10:31.499 --> 00:10:36.079
to something projected on a two-dimensional
screen. But no amount of, no amount of knowing

00:10:36.079 --> 00:10:39.170
what I just told you is gonna make it look
any different; it still looks longer. It's

00:10:39.170 --> 00:10:43.709
an illusion, it's built in to the way our
perceptual systems work and we would argue

00:10:43.709 --> 00:10:47.190
that illusions like the illusion of attention
are built in to the way we think about our

00:10:47.190 --> 00:10:51.209
own minds. I see someone there going like
this and trying to like, imagine it. If I

00:10:51.209 --> 00:10:54.139
had a stick up there I could prove it to you.
I could stretch a stick out and then move

00:10:54.139 --> 00:11:00.839
it around. That's what I do when I teach this
to students. Trust me on this one. It's really

00:11:00.839 --> 00:11:05.230
built in to the structure of how we understand
our own minds. I see someone who's still doing

00:11:05.230 --> 00:11:06.230
it; they still don't believe me.

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:07.999
[laughter]

00:11:07.999 --> 00:11:14.920
Trust me, please. I'm up here giving a talk.
You're supposed to trust me. So, so, this

00:11:14.920 --> 00:11:19.059
illusion of attention, the more we thought
about it, we realized was actually an example

00:11:19.059 --> 00:11:26.249
of a more general phenomenon about the mind
and we call this the idea of every day illusions.

00:11:26.249 --> 00:11:30.519
So, I'm gonna get a couple of definitions
out on the screen now for what I'm going to

00:11:30.519 --> 00:11:34.999
be talking about for the rest of the time
today. Every day illusions are intuitive,

00:11:34.999 --> 00:11:40.029
commonsense beliefs that we all have about
how our own minds work that are systematically

00:11:40.029 --> 00:11:48.129
wrong, not easy to overcome, and can get us
into big trouble if we aren't aware of them.

00:11:48.129 --> 00:11:51.329
Now, one way the illusion of attention can
get us into big trouble is the way that it

00:11:51.329 --> 00:11:55.759
causes us to talk on our cell phones while
we're driving. The illusion causes us to talk

00:11:55.759 --> 00:11:59.620
on our cell phones while we're driving because
it convinces us that we're able to see and

00:11:59.620 --> 00:12:03.129
notice everything we need to do while we're
driving just as well when we're talking on

00:12:03.129 --> 00:12:08.879
a phone as when we're not talking on a phone.
The illusion of attention tells us that because

00:12:08.879 --> 00:12:12.519
we have this rich perceptual experience, we
see the road in front of us. It's not like

00:12:12.519 --> 00:12:15.889
we're looking someplace else to talk on the
phone. We see the road in front of us; we're

00:12:15.889 --> 00:12:18.720
getting the same visual input hitting our
retinas and going into our visual systems

00:12:18.720 --> 00:12:22.929
and so on, that we must be noticing and perceiving
all the important stuff out there. And that's

00:12:22.929 --> 00:12:26.819
actually not true. When you're talking on
the cell phone, you're depleting a central

00:12:26.819 --> 00:12:32.089
resource of attention that actually applies
to all perceptual modalities and to thinking

00:12:32.089 --> 00:12:35.220
in general, not just vision. So, talking on
the phone, even though that's an auditory

00:12:35.220 --> 00:12:40.290
language task, decreases your ability to notice
unexpected things. And it's noticing unexpected

00:12:40.290 --> 00:12:43.089
things which is really what keeps you out
of most accidents on the road. You know when

00:12:43.089 --> 00:12:48.259
someone cuts you off or when someone goes
into the walkway or when you're in somebody's

00:12:48.259 --> 00:12:52.869
blind spot and so on. If we didn't have this
illusion, if we really understood how limited

00:12:52.869 --> 00:12:56.290
our perceptual inattention systems would be,
we probably wouldn't do things like talk on

00:12:56.290 --> 00:12:59.379
cell phones. And of course, incidentally,
by the way, it's not holding the phone that's

00:12:59.379 --> 00:13:02.009
the problem, it's not the number of hands
you have driving, it's the amount of your

00:13:02.009 --> 00:13:06.480
mind you have paying attention to the task
of driving. So, hands free phones don't really

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:10.730
solve the problem, either. Now notice that
I said that these illusions are intuitive

00:13:10.730 --> 00:13:17.109
beliefs. So, by intuition, I mean a kind of
rapid thinking that we aren't even aware we're

00:13:17.109 --> 00:13:21.230
doing most of the time. Intuition is what
we're using when we make a quick judgment

00:13:21.230 --> 00:13:25.720
or decision without thinking about it, which
is to say that intuition comprises most of

00:13:25.720 --> 00:13:29.579
the thinking we do in our lives. Now I realize
that there are other definitions of intuition.

00:13:29.579 --> 00:13:32.540
Some people think of intuition as some kind
of spiritual phenomenon where you just sort

00:13:32.540 --> 00:13:36.350
of come into contact with the truth or something
like that, through some ineffable process.

00:13:36.350 --> 00:13:40.439
That's not really what I'm talking about.
I'm talking about rapid thinking and decisions

00:13:40.439 --> 00:13:44.459
made without reflection. So when we pick up
the cell phone and talk while we're driving,

00:13:44.459 --> 00:13:47.800
we're doing that because of an intuition that
tells us that we're not driving any worse.

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:51.970
We haven't really stopped to analyze the problem
very carefully or think about research on

00:13:51.970 --> 00:13:56.549
attention and so on, we just go with it. We
don't feel like we're driving any worse when

00:13:56.549 --> 00:14:00.230
we're talking on the phone. So that's, those
are every day illusions and in our book, we

00:14:00.230 --> 00:14:03.749
talk about six every day illusions. I'm gonna
talk about the rest of them for the rest of

00:14:03.749 --> 00:14:08.480
this talk and as well as that, I'm gonna talk
about intuition a little bit. Here's another

00:14:08.480 --> 00:14:13.500
example of an everyday illusion. This one
is called the illusion of memory. The illusion

00:14:13.500 --> 00:14:19.509
of memory is the idea that our memories are
more complete, detailed, accurate, permanent

00:14:19.509 --> 00:14:25.619
and objective than they really are. Those
qualities detail, accuracy, permanence, objectivity

00:14:25.619 --> 00:14:30.470
and completeness are qualities that we act
as though our memories have in much greater

00:14:30.470 --> 00:14:34.189
abundance than they really do. Now of course,
you may say, "Yeah, I don't remember what

00:14:34.189 --> 00:14:37.509
I had for breakfast three weeks ago." I'm
not talking about that kind of memory failure.

00:14:37.509 --> 00:14:42.360
I'm talking about something much larger than
that. For example, you're gonna see now a

00:14:42.360 --> 00:14:45.819
video of an experiment done by Dan Simons,
my co-author of the book, and his colleague,

00:14:45.819 --> 00:14:51.290
Dan Levin, when they were grad students at
Cornell. This is an experiment where an experimenter

00:14:51.290 --> 00:15:00.279
would approach a pedestrian on a courtyard
