really careful logical deduction and scientific
analysis proved him to be a forger? I think,

00:29:59.521 --> 00:30:03.639
actually, that the Thomas J. Wise case is
probably much more representative of the relationship

00:30:03.639 --> 00:30:08.179
between intuition and logical analysis in
the case of art forgeries. I will bet you

00:30:08.179 --> 00:30:13.080
that many forgers go to their graves having
fooled everyone and never get detected. Usually,

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:18.999
it's a sort of intuitive thinking that accepts
these things as accurate and only scientific

00:30:18.999 --> 00:30:22.950
analysis, or some kind of logical analysis
that proves them wrong. For example, the Hitler

00:30:22.950 --> 00:30:26.890
Diaries were accepted as genuine and made
public in Germany, until it turned out that

00:30:26.890 --> 00:30:30.669
the paper they were written on was made after
World War II. So, they could only have been

00:30:30.669 --> 00:30:34.179
authentic if Hitler was down there in Brazil
writing them out or something like that, after

00:30:34.179 --> 00:30:40.480
World War II was over, and sending them back.
Now, what we call the myth of intuition is

00:30:40.480 --> 00:30:45.429
this idea that intuition has special powers
as a mode of thinking to figure things out

00:30:45.429 --> 00:30:52.909
that rational analysis and other forms of
thinking cannot do. At this point, now statues,

00:30:52.909 --> 00:30:56.029
even a ten million dollar statue, well it's
just statues, what's the big deal if people

00:30:56.029 --> 00:31:01.519
think this way? Its fast, it's efficient,
doesn't cause too much damage, except to museums

00:31:01.519 --> 00:31:06.149
and art collectors and they're not really
all that sympathetic. Who are the real victims

00:31:06.149 --> 00:31:11.899
here? Well, at this point, this is where this
man comes into our story. In case you don't

00:31:11.899 --> 00:31:17.360
recognize him, this is Bernard Madoff, the
biggest and most famous Ponzi schemer in world

00:31:17.360 --> 00:31:24.340
financial history. Now what does Bernard Madoff
have to do with the myth of intuition? Well,

00:31:24.340 --> 00:31:28.860
one thing that's not realized often about
Madoff is the real story of why he was not

00:31:28.860 --> 00:31:35.610
caught before he wound up engaging in 50 billion
dollars worth of fraud and looting lots of

00:31:35.610 --> 00:31:41.879
institutions and individuals out of all of
their funds? The whistle, the Inspector General

00:31:41.879 --> 00:31:45.730
of the Securities and Exchange Commission
did an exhaustive report on this and documented

00:31:45.730 --> 00:31:49.669
the fact that the SEC investigated Madoff
many times over the years because they had

00:31:49.669 --> 00:31:53.379
received tips from people. They had their
suspicions that something was wrong. And here

00:31:53.379 --> 00:31:58.759
he explains why they did not actually catch
Madoff. This is a quote from the Inspector

00:31:58.759 --> 00:32:03.830
General of the SEC. He wrote, "In one of the
examinations that the SEC conducted, they

00:32:03.830 --> 00:32:07.619
asked Madoff how he was able to achieve these
returns. Madoff's returns were extraordinary

00:32:07.619 --> 00:32:11.700
and always consistent. He never had a down
period, no matter how bad the market. And

00:32:11.700 --> 00:32:15.279
they asked him, "How are you able to do this?"
Bernie Madoff said to them that he had a 'gut

00:32:15.279 --> 00:32:18.809
feel' of how to time the market. They asked
him, what is the basis for his gut feel. And

00:32:18.809 --> 00:32:21.940
he said it was his observations of the trading
room. He said he could actually sit on the

00:32:21.940 --> 00:32:25.809
trading room floor and 'feel the market' and
know exactly when to buy and exactly when

00:32:25.809 --> 00:32:28.980
to sell. And Madoff always bought at the right
price, and always sold at the right price,

00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:34.629
day after day, year after year. Inexplicably,
the SEC just accepted these answers and went

00:32:34.629 --> 00:32:41.610
on." Now, I think the most important word
in this whole passage is one that they didn't

00:32:41.610 --> 00:32:46.960
underline, and that is the word "inexplicably."
This behavior's only inexplicable if you forget

00:32:46.960 --> 00:32:50.929
about the fact that people actually believe
that it is possible to use one's intuition,

00:32:50.929 --> 00:32:55.179
or gut feels, to time the market and make
all kinds of other significant decisions in

00:32:55.179 --> 00:33:01.869
ways that, in ways that rational analysis,
or logic, or other kinds of methods, thinking

00:33:01.869 --> 00:33:06.460
can't match. So, it's only inexplicable if
you don't realize that that myth is out there

00:33:06.460 --> 00:33:12.299
and that we think about intuition that way
a lot of the time. Now, this raises another

00:33:12.299 --> 00:33:18.049
question, well how is, what else contributed
to Bernie Madoff's success? I think it's interesting

00:33:18.049 --> 00:33:22.789
and it plays in to one of our other, one of
our other illusions. The whistle blower in

00:33:22.789 --> 00:33:29.379
the Madoff case, Harry Markopolos, wrote extensively
about this. And he provides some interesting

00:33:29.379 --> 00:33:34.769
quotes to explain what was going on in people's
minds when they encountered Bernard Madoff.

00:33:34.769 --> 00:33:38.600
Well, Simona Suh, who was an investigator
in the SECs New York office, said that Madoff

00:33:38.600 --> 00:33:43.100
[quote] "didn't fit the profile of a Ponzi
schemer in the world that we knew then." Now

00:33:43.100 --> 00:33:48.090
what did she mean by this? Well, as Markopolos
tells us, 'There's a reason why Madoff was

00:33:48.090 --> 00:33:51.980
able to pull off the largest financial crime
in history. Madoff was so smooth, so convincing

00:33:51.980 --> 00:33:56.440
that even an experienced journalist like Mike
Ocrant, (who had uncovered other Ponzi schemes,)

00:33:56.440 --> 00:34:00.010
came away from that interview doubting what
he knew to be true.' So, Ocrant had actually

00:34:00.010 --> 00:34:03.630
investigated Madoff, determined that he was
a Ponzi schemer, and went to confront him

00:34:03.630 --> 00:34:06.549
with this information and get his side of
the story, and at the end of the interview,

00:34:06.549 --> 00:34:12.329
he wasn't even sure anymore himself. Ocrant,
himself, was the editor of an industry publication

00:34:12.329 --> 00:34:16.419
for hedge funds said [quote] "He never complained;
he was responsive to every question. He did

00:34:16.419 --> 00:34:23.599
it without hesitation. There wasn't even a
hint of guilt or shame or remorse." So, sometimes

00:34:23.599 --> 00:34:29.349
the way criminals are able to pull off their
crimes is by exploiting what we call in the

00:34:29.349 --> 00:34:36.579
book, the illusion of confidence. Interestingly,
the word "con man" has the same root as confidence.

00:34:36.579 --> 00:34:42.500
The illusion of confidence has two aspects.
One of them is that we tend to interpret another

00:34:42.500 --> 00:34:48.980
person's confidence, their smoothness, their
quick answers, their strong presentations

00:34:48.980 --> 00:34:55.500
an indication of honesty, accuracy, truthfulness,
skill, competence, good memory, whatever it

00:34:55.500 --> 00:35:00.390
is they're trying to convince us of, the more
confident they are, the more we believe them.

00:35:00.390 --> 00:35:04.109
Now, it's of course perhaps true that people
who are right should be more confident, but

00:35:04.109 --> 00:35:10.750
we over interpret that connection; we take
it for more than it actually is. Now, this

00:35:10.750 --> 00:35:14.049
is our third every day illusion after attention
and memory. Now we're at the illusion of confidence.

00:35:14.049 --> 00:35:21.170
Madoff is a little bit unusual as a criminal.
And he's like the James Bond master villain,

00:35:21.170 --> 00:35:24.770
like in his secret hideout with all the fancy
gadgets and so on. This time it was at the

00:35:24.770 --> 00:35:29.619
top of a skyscraper in New York, not in some
Caribbean island, but he's really not typical

00:35:29.619 --> 00:35:33.680
of criminals. Most criminals are not as good
as Madoff; they don't get away with 50 billion

00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:40.880
dollar schemes for that long. Most criminals
are actually fairly incompetent. So now, to

00:35:40.880 --> 00:35:44.450
illustrate this point, I would like to ask
the person who received an envelope from me

00:35:44.450 --> 00:35:51.050
earlier to please stand up now. I handed out
an envelope earlier to someone. OK. So can

00:35:51.050 --> 00:35:56.880
you open that envelope and show us what's
inside? What is that?

00:35:56.880 --> 00:35:59.119
&gt;&gt;audience #5: I'm assuming a fake bill for
one million dollars.

00:35:59.119 --> 00:36:01.190
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: It's a one million dollar
bill, correct?

00:36:01.190 --> 00:36:02.190
[audience #5 laughs]

00:36:02.190 --> 00:36:03.190
OK, so what's your name, by the way?

00:36:03.190 --> 00:36:04.190
&gt;&gt;audience #5: Jessica.

00:36:04.190 --> 00:36:07.020
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: Jessica. OK, so Jessica,
what do you think would happen if you went

00:36:07.020 --> 00:36:12.200
out to the supermarket and tried to use that
one million dollar bill to pay for your next

00:36:12.200 --> 00:36:13.200
batch of groceries?

00:36:13.200 --> 00:36:15.921
&gt;&gt;audience #5: They would probably laugh at
me.

00:36:15.921 --> 00:36:17.690
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: They would probably laugh
at you and they probably wouldn't cash it

00:36:17.690 --> 00:36:18.690
for you, right?

00:36:18.690 --> 00:36:19.690
&gt;&gt;audience #5: Right.

00:36:19.690 --> 00:36:26.560
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: OK. So, Jessica is much smarter,
it turns out, than this man, a man who flew

00:36:26.560 --> 00:36:31.540
into a rage at the Giant Eagle supermarket
when employees refused to cash a million-dollar

00:36:31.540 --> 00:36:32.540
bill.

00:36:32.540 --> 00:36:33.540
[laughter]

00:36:33.540 --> 00:36:38.510
This was an Associated Press story from Pittsburgh.
Now, it's interesting that a guy went in to

00:36:38.510 --> 00:36:42.530
a supermarket and tried to cash a million-dollar
bill. What's more interesting is that he flew

00:36:42.530 --> 00:36:46.350
into a rage when they refused to do this,
suggesting that perhaps he thought that they

00:36:46.350 --> 00:36:50.950
should, or they would negotiate his million-dollar
bill. I also wonder where he got the million

00:36:50.950 --> 00:36:55.031
dollar bill, but in any case. Maybe it was
handed out at a talk he went to.

00:36:55.031 --> 00:36:58.190
[laughter]

00:36:58.190 --> 00:37:03.560
What this illustrates is a mismatch between
this guy's assessment of his own abilities

00:37:03.560 --> 00:37:07.121
and his actual ability. He thinks he's better
at crime than he really is if he thinks he

00:37:07.121 --> 00:37:12.490
can get away with this, is this one. According
to Inspector Gareth Woods of the Cheshire

00:37:12.490 --> 00:37:16.180
Police, "there are some pretty stupid criminals
around, but to leave your own name at the

00:37:16.180 --> 00:37:21.770
scene of the crime takes the biscuit." Now,
the crime was graffiti and it was committed

00:37:21.770 --> 00:37:28.190
by someone named Peter Addison, who wrote,
"Peter Addison was here" on a wall. Another

00:37:28.190 --> 00:37:33.640
stupid criminal. And then finally, this man.
Lieutenant Terry Hastings said, "I just don't

00:37:33.640 --> 00:37:36.420
know why he didn't see a uniformed police
officer standing basically right in front

00:37:36.420 --> 00:37:41.569
of him. My guess is he's just not the brightest
of people." Now, what he's referring to is

00:37:41.569 --> 00:37:45.569
this gentleman right here, who attempted to
rob a bank where there was a police officer

00:37:45.569 --> 00:37:49.299
sitting in the lobby of the bank the entire
time. If you can find this video online, by

00:37:49.299 --> 00:37:53.260
the way, it's actually very funny. The police
officer tries to arrest him, but he resists

00:37:53.260 --> 00:37:56.801
and they wind up wrestling in the bank and
running around the bank chasing each other

00:37:56.801 --> 00:37:59.390
for quite a while. It's very entertaining
surveillance camera footage.

00:37:59.390 --> 00:38:02.049
[laughter]

00:38:02.049 --> 00:38:05.110
The guy had come in to the bank and cased
it for a couple of minutes before he actually

00:38:05.110 --> 00:38:08.300
went up to the teller and tried to rob it
and that whole time the video shows the guy

00:38:08.300 --> 00:38:14.049
sitting right there behind the desk, waiting
to catch him. Now, Lieutenant Terry Hastings

00:38:14.049 --> 00:38:17.360
is suffering a little bit from the illusion
of attention because as we've all seen, it

00:38:17.360 --> 00:38:21.020
is possible to walk around some place and
not notice something important that's happening

00:38:21.020 --> 00:38:25.890
in front of you; that's the illusion of attention.
Nonetheless, all these examples illustrate

00:38:25.890 --> 00:38:33.930
criminals who seem to think that they're better
at crime than they really are. Now, [pause]

00:38:33.930 --> 00:38:37.630
this illustrates the second aspect of the
illusion of confidence, which is that we tend

00:38:37.630 --> 00:38:43.640
to overrate our own abilities in various areas.
We're overconfident in our own skills. Let

00:38:43.640 --> 00:38:49.060
me try a little test on you to see how overconfident
you are in your own skills. I have a question

00:38:49.060 --> 00:38:53.650
that I got that I adapted from a study by
Justin Kruger and David Dunning, two very

00:38:53.650 --> 00:38:59.809
clever social psychologists. For each one
of you, I'd like you to think what percent

00:38:59.809 --> 00:39:04.290
of Google employees have a worse sense of
humor than your own? Now, I know you're all

00:39:04.290 --> 00:39:08.110
here at my talk, so you're probably some of
the funnier people here, but try to be honest

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:11.710
with yourself and think about what percentage
of Google employees have a worse sense of

00:39:11.710 --> 00:39:16.170
humor than your own. Just get a number in
your head, what that percentage might be.

00:39:16.170 --> 00:39:20.750
And now you've got that percentage, let's
test your own sense of humor and see how funny

00:39:20.750 --> 00:39:24.910
you really are. I'm gonna give you two jokes
and would like you to tell me which one is

00:39:24.910 --> 00:39:25.910
funnier.

00:39:25.910 --> 00:39:27.849
[laughter]

00:39:27.849 --> 00:39:33.690
Here's joke one. Question: What is as big
as a man, but weighs nothing? Answer: His

00:39:33.690 --> 00:39:38.599
shadow. Joke two. I heard someone laugh.

00:39:38.599 --> 00:39:40.470
[laughter]

00:39:40.470 --> 00:39:44.150
Joke two. If a kid asks where rain comes from,
I think a cute thing to tell him is "God is

00:39:44.150 --> 00:39:47.910
crying." And if he asks why God is crying,
another cute thing to tell him is "probably

00:39:47.910 --> 00:39:49.130
because of something you did."

00:39:49.130 --> 00:39:51.160
[laughter]

00:39:51.160 --> 00:39:55.549
Now, by actual laughter, it seems like most
of you think joke two is funnier than joke

00:39:55.549 --> 00:40:00.619
one and you should pat yourselves on the back
because in fact, when Kruger and Dunning presented

00:40:00.619 --> 00:40:04.119
these two jokes, as well as a number of other
jokes to a panel of professional comedians,

00:40:04.119 --> 00:40:07.799
the professional comedians rated joke two
as the funniest out of the entire group and

00:40:07.799 --> 00:40:13.730
joke one as the least funny out of the entire
group. And by using these ratings by professional

00:40:13.730 --> 00:40:16.859
comedians, and then giving all these same
jokes to students in their experiment, they

00:40:16.859 --> 00:40:22.280
were able to figure out how well student ratings
of funniness of jokes agreed with professional

00:40:22.280 --> 00:40:26.119
comedian ratings of funniness of jokes. And
they used those correspondences between the

00:40:26.119 --> 00:40:31.109
students and the comedians as a more or less
objective measure of how good the student's

00:40:31.109 --> 00:40:34.039
sense of humor was. Now, of course it's really
how well their sense of humor matches that

00:40:34.039 --> 00:40:37.859
of a professional comedian, but a professional
comedian is paid to understand what's funny

00:40:37.859 --> 00:40:41.270
and to implement that in their own, in their
own act. So, it's not really as bad a test

00:40:41.270 --> 00:40:48.819
as you might think. So they compared how funny
people actually were with how funny they thought

00:40:48.819 --> 00:40:56.730
they were. And here's what they found. The
straight diagonal line just indicates the

00:40:56.730 --> 00:41:01.599
actual test score on this humor test, so those
who were in the bottom quartile, by definition,

00:41:01.599 --> 00:41:05.740
scored 12 and a half percent in this test.
And those who were in the second quartile,

00:41:05.740 --> 00:41:09.030
by definition, 37 and a half percent and so
on if you just divide them into quartiles.

00:41:09.030 --> 00:41:14.480
But notice that the perceived ability, that
is, what percentage of people who they thought

00:41:14.480 --> 00:41:18.950
were less funny then they were, is actually
above 50 for all of these groups. And the

00:41:18.950 --> 00:41:24.130
largest difference between perceived funniness
and actual funniness is found in those who

00:41:24.130 --> 00:41:25.130
were the least funny.

00:41:25.130 --> 00:41:26.130
[laughter]

00:41:26.130 --> 00:41:30.569
So, this was dubbed by Kruger and Dunning,
the unskilled and unaware of it phenomenon.

00:41:30.569 --> 00:41:34.420
That those who were least skilled at something
are least aware of their actual skill level,

00:41:34.420 --> 00:41:38.039
or exhibit the greatest discrepancy between
how good they think they are and how good

00:41:38.039 --> 00:41:43.410
they really are. Now, of course once again
it's just like the statues before and so on.

00:41:43.410 --> 00:41:47.460
This is sense of humor and sense of humor
 -- maybe it's not that important, although

00:41:47.460 --> 00:41:49.901
I do have to say that it is right up there
in all the personal ads. You always see sense

00:41:49.901 --> 00:41:54.130
of humor in all the dating sites and so on,
it's number one. And incidentally, I just

00:41:54.130 --> 00:41:58.940
heard of some recent research that is not
published yet, so I don't wanna talk about

00:41:58.940 --> 00:42:02.170
it too much, but someone said that sense of
humor is actually one of the best predictors

00:42:02.170 --> 00:42:06.530
of how good you are in bed, it turns out.
So, it's really more important than we think

00:42:06.530 --> 00:42:07.530
sometimes.

00:42:07.530 --> 00:42:08.530
[laughter]

00:42:08.530 --> 00:42:12.210
Nonetheless, it is a little bit; it is a little
bit fanciful. Now what about something more

00:42:12.210 --> 00:42:15.140
serious and more important, and especially
something more objective, where instead of

00:42:15.140 --> 00:42:19.190
using these kind of tests, we really know
how good people are? Are people still overconfident

00:42:19.190 --> 00:42:22.970
in their own abilities when they have all
the information they need to truly know how

00:42:22.970 --> 00:42:27.750
good they are? Well, Dan Simons and I, along
with Dan Benjamin, who is now an economics

00:42:27.750 --> 00:42:33.010
professor at Cornell, a few years ago, did
a study to look at this. We went to the environment

00:42:33.010 --> 00:42:36.799
of competitive chess and we visited chess
tournaments like this one. Now, chess is an

00:42:36.799 --> 00:42:40.690
interesting arena to study because chess has
an objective statistical rating system that

00:42:40.690 --> 00:42:44.420
tells you, in essence, exactly how good you
are, will tell you exactly what your probability

00:42:44.420 --> 00:42:48.010
is at beating anyone else based on their rating
and the ratings are frequently updated, players

00:42:48.010 --> 00:42:50.600
all know their own ratings and most of them
have a pretty good idea how the ratings are

00:42:50.600 --> 00:42:55.160
actually calculated. So, we went to this chess
tournament and asked them two simple questions

00:42:55.160 --> 00:43:01.220
of the players. One, what's your current chess
rating? And two, what should your rating be

00:43:01.220 --> 00:43:02.840
to accurately reflect your skill?

00:43:02.840 --> 00:43:03.840
[laughter]

00:43:03.840 --> 00:43:10.039
So, we got two numbers from them and we simply
subtracted them. And it turns out that, on

00:43:10.039 --> 00:43:13.890
average, players think that they are significantly
underrated, meaning they think their ratings

00:43:13.890 --> 00:43:18.049
should be higher to reflect their true skill.
In fact, they think they are so underrated

00:43:18.049 --> 00:43:23.250
that their true self should beat their rated
self by a score of two to one in a match,

00:43:23.250 --> 00:43:27.319
which is a really significant difference.
They think they are significantly underrated.

00:43:27.319 --> 00:43:32.000
And moreover, those at the lower end of the
rating scale, the worst chess players, think

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:36.170
they are more underrated then those at the
top end of the scale. So, unskilled unaware

00:43:36.170 --> 00:43:39.570
of it is not just an artifact of something
where we don't have a good idea how good we

00:43:39.570 --> 00:43:42.950
are. It's something that applies even when
we have objective information about our own

00:43:42.950 --> 00:43:47.230
skills. It really shows that the illusion
of confidence is part of our self assessment

00:43:47.230 --> 00:43:55.350
across the board and is resistant to data
in many ways. Now, that was the illusion of

00:43:55.350 --> 00:44:00.360
confidence, and let me move on to a related
illusion, which can be illustrated best by

00:44:00.360 --> 00:44:06.220
an experiment by the British psychologist,
Rebecca Lawson. Again, very simple. No high-tech

00:44:06.220 --> 00:44:10.930
experiments here today. Rebecca Lawson asked
subjects, how well do you understand how a

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:14.859
bicycle works? Asked them to rate on a scale
of zero to seven how well they understand

00:44:14.859 --> 00:44:19.819
how a bicycle works; zero meaning "I have
no idea"; seven meaning "I'm really very knowledgeable

00:44:19.819 --> 00:44:25.660
about how bicycles work." And then she surprised
them with the following question: Draw a bicycle,

00:44:25.660 --> 00:44:33.040
being sure to show the frame, pedals, and
chain. You might think for a second how well

00:44:33.040 --> 00:44:40.161
you could do this task. It's also fun to transpose
the whole situation to a toilet. How well

00:44:40.161 --> 00:44:43.630
do you understand how a toilet works, and
now draw the mechanism of a toilet. Now, you

00:44:43.630 --> 00:44:47.010
guys, there are probably a lot of engineers
in the audience and so on, so you guys are

00:44:47.010 --> 00:44:50.750
probably a bad audience for this thing and
you would do better than the subjects in Lawson's

00:44:50.750 --> 00:44:52.760
study. Here's some of what they produced.

