00:59:38.299 --> 00:59:43.769
day versus somebody who doesn't ride a bicycle,
if you could just talk some more about that.

00:59:43.769 --> 00:59:46.430
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: Yeah, that's a really good
question. I did throw that in as kind of an

00:59:46.430 --> 00:59:50.589
offhand observation and the reason why I did
was that we haven't actually done any studies

00:59:50.589 --> 00:59:56.089
on this. I think it would be really interesting
to do some cognitive psychology research on

00:59:56.089 --> 01:00:00.040
what's the measurable effect of having more
or less access to information about a particular

01:00:00.040 --> 01:00:03.940
topic. How does that affect how much, how
well you think you understand that and so

01:00:03.940 --> 01:00:07.869
on and I can't really, I can't really tell
you what the results would be because we haven't

01:00:07.869 --> 01:00:12.080
actually done that yet, so it's more of a
hypothesis than a subtle conclusion. And I

01:00:12.080 --> 01:00:15.589
don't mean to say, by the way, that having
access to more information, heaven forbid

01:00:15.589 --> 01:00:19.410
in this building, to say that having access
to more information is a bad thing. I think

01:00:19.410 --> 01:00:25.000
it's undoubtedly, overall an extremely great
thing, but there may be some side effects

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:31.710
on our perception of how much we actually
understand. And I base this partly on my observation

01:00:31.710 --> 01:00:38.329
of students sometimes that it's easy for students
in courses to think they understand things

01:00:38.329 --> 01:00:41.319
better than they really do and I think part
of the reason for that is that the information

01:00:41.319 --> 01:00:44.340
is so accessible. Not only is there a textbook,
but they can look things up on Wikipedia and

01:00:44.340 --> 01:00:47.600
now we put our PowerPoint slides online, they
go to lectures and so on. The information

01:00:47.600 --> 01:00:51.029
comes at them in a lot of different forms
a lot of the time, but I don't think it necessarily

01:00:51.029 --> 01:00:55.309
helps them understand how well they understand
the topic. They still say after they did badly

01:00:55.309 --> 01:00:57.960
on the test, they say, "Well, how did I do
so badly on the test? I really looked at all

01:00:57.960 --> 01:01:03.420
that information." And so on. But I definitely
agree that this is a very fruitful area for

01:01:03.420 --> 01:01:06.080
more experiments that I would like to work
on.

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:11.410
&gt;&gt;audience #7: But so you seem to be suggesting
that you think that somehow easier access

01:01:11.410 --> 01:01:15.740
to information is making people conflate,
I don't know, like--

01:01:15.740 --> 01:01:17.560
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: What's in their head with
what's out in the world?

01:01:17.560 --> 01:01:24.220
&gt;&gt;audience #7: Or maybe in the last example,
like facts with some, I don't know, deep understanding

01:01:24.220 --> 01:01:25.220
or--

01:01:25.220 --> 01:01:33.210
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: Yeah, essentially yes -- that
the easier it is to access information the

01:01:33.210 --> 01:01:36.769
harder it is to tell the difference between
information that we actually know and information

01:01:36.769 --> 01:01:44.819
that we can easily retrieve. That's, that's
the hypothesis. And you look skeptical, which

01:01:44.819 --> 01:01:45.819
I think is good.

01:01:45.819 --> 01:01:46.819
[Chris laughs]

01:01:46.819 --> 01:01:49.430
Cause it definitely hasn't been, it definitely
hasn't been tested extensively. I think it's

01:01:49.430 --> 01:01:52.000
an interesting hypothesis for investigation.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:53.010
&gt;&gt;audience #7: Thank you.

01:01:53.010 --> 01:01:58.650
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: Thanks. There was someone
over here, or maybe he's over, back over here

01:01:58.650 --> 01:02:00.450
now. Oh, OK. Yeah?

01:02:00.450 --> 01:02:04.119
&gt;&gt;audience #8: I just had a question about
that million dollar bill you gave to her.

01:02:04.119 --> 01:02:05.119
[Chris laughs]

01:02:05.119 --> 01:02:09.009
I've seen videos of, I don't know how real
these videos are, they're from some like,

01:02:09.009 --> 01:02:14.640
mentalist guy, but he like, pays for things
with blank, with like white paper--

01:02:14.640 --> 01:02:15.640
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: Mm-hmm.

01:02:15.640 --> 01:02:18.549
&gt;&gt;audience #8: that's roughly in the shape
of dollar bills. And I was just, I mean, is

01:02:18.549 --> 01:02:19.890
that the same thing?

01:02:19.890 --> 01:02:23.759
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: I haven't seen the videos
you're talking about, but I suspect what's

01:02:23.759 --> 01:02:30.130
going on there is that if you distract the
people in certain ways from what you're doing,

01:02:30.130 --> 01:02:32.932
they may just take what you hand them and
stick them in the cash register or something

01:02:32.932 --> 01:02:36.170
like that. Now, of course, if this guy wanted
to buy a milkshake with a million-dollar bill,

01:02:36.170 --> 01:02:40.029
he probably could have got away with it. It
was the expecting change that was the problem

01:02:40.029 --> 01:02:42.890
and in order to get your change from a million-dollar
bill, the cashier's gotta look at it and see

01:02:42.890 --> 01:02:45.880
that it's a million-dollar bill and so on.
So, I don't think it's exactly the same--

01:02:45.880 --> 01:02:46.880
&gt;&gt;audience #8: Sure.

01:02:46.880 --> 01:02:49.630
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: but in a way, a lot of what
mentalists do and magicians, of course, is

01:02:49.630 --> 01:02:52.430
manipulate your attention. So, they manipulate
what you're paying attention to and what you're

01:02:52.430 --> 01:02:56.010
thinking about at any particular time, it's
very easy with all the stuff that we can miss

01:02:56.010 --> 01:02:59.589
in the world to imagine that we could miss
actually what we're stuffing in the cash register

01:02:59.589 --> 01:03:02.030
or something like that. Thanks.

01:03:02.030 --> 01:03:06.740
&gt;&gt;audience #9: So, in the experiments that
you did, you mentioned that there were some

01:03:06.740 --> 01:03:10.930
people who were perceptive, who noticed that
experimenters had changed or whatever.

01:03:10.930 --> 01:03:11.930
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: Mm-hmm.

01:03:11.930 --> 01:03:15.089
&gt;&gt;audience #9: I was wondering if there was
anything else about these people. Were they

01:03:15.089 --> 01:03:19.079
happier? Were they sadder? Were they miserable?
Had they had three divorces? I don't know

01:03:19.079 --> 01:03:20.170
anything that you might have come up with.

01:03:20.170 --> 01:03:22.109
&gt;&gt;Chris Chabris: Well, we didn't test a three
divorce hypothesis.

01:03:22.109 --> 01:03:24.440
[laughter]

01:03:24.440 --> 01:03:31.819
That might correlate with the happiness or
sadness. In general, the answer is that nothing

01:03:31.819 --> 01:03:38.369
has been found that at all strongly predicts
whether people notice unexpected things in

01:03:38.369 --> 01:03:43.910
inattentional blindness experiments or noticed
changes in change blindness experiments. Things

01:03:43.910 --> 01:03:47.150
you think might, like their working memory
capacity, how much stuff can they maintain

01:03:47.150 --> 01:03:51.150
in memory at one time, doesn't seem to. Dan
Simons has been doing some research on this.

01:03:51.150 --> 01:03:55.750
I even, by the way, ran a study where we included
the gorilla test, along with a lot of other

01:03:55.750 --> 01:03:59.220
tests and then we got DNA from the subjects
and looked to see if there were any genes

01:03:59.220 --> 01:04:03.079
that the gorilla noticers had that the missers
didn't and we didn't find anything. But, of

01:04:03.079 --> 01:04:06.330
course, it's very hard to find, find genes
for things like that so I was a little bit

01:04:06.330 --> 01:04:11.390
quixotic, but Dan has found maybe some faint
hints that personality variables might affect

01:04:11.390 --> 01:04:16.799
it, but they're extremely small effects and
hard to see so that your success or failure

01:04:16.799 --> 01:04:21.680
at noticing something is really a bad personality
test, a really bad measure of anything. And

01:04:21.680 --> 01:04:26.780
I think most of it is circumstance and luck
and whatever's happen, whatever's going on

01:04:26.780 --> 01:04:32.000
in your brain at that time and so on. There's,
you know? I hesitate to just call it random

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:35.440
because there's nothing truly random, but
from our point of view it would be random.

01:04:35.440 --> 01:04:36.440
Thanks.

01:04:36.440 --> 01:04:42.260
&gt;&gt;audience #10: I have another question about
the million-dollar bill experiment. So, you

01:04:42.260 --> 01:04:45.539
use that as an example, or at least the way
